I SUGGESTED THAT BETTER QUALITY DRUMS ARE USED TO SHIP THIS MATERIAL IN THE FUTURE.

THE LIQUID WHICH HAD LEAKED OUT EVAPORATED. DOCK PERSONNEL NEED TO USE COMMON SENSE WHEN LOADING SKIDS ON TOP OF SKIDS TO ENSURE THAT NO DAMAGE OCCURS.

column168: WHEN LOADING FOR DELIVERY 2 PARTS OF ETHANOL SOLUTION A CLASS 3 LIQUID, WAS DAMAGED FROM A FORK BLADE. THE PAILS WERE COOLED WITH LIQUID FORCED OUT AROUND THE CAP AREA. THE PARTS WERE RESEALED AND THE SHIPMENT DELIVERED TO THE CONSIGNEE.

WE RECEIVED IN A SHIPMENT OF 12 CARTONS OF CEMENT PATCHING KITS.  AS CARTAGE PERSONNEL WERE UNLOADING THE LID, AN EMPLOYEE TOUCHED A CARTON THAT HAD DROPPED OFF THE PALLET AND HIS HAND CAME IN CONTACT WITH A RESINOUS SUBSTANCE.  HE IMMEDIATELY WASHED HIS HANDS AND INFORMED ME ABOUT THE SPILL.  I INSPECTED THE CARTON AND DISCOVERED IT CONTAINED A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL (UN1760) I CLEANED THE SPILL PER THE DOT'S EMERGENCY RESPONSE GUIDE.  I THEN PUT THE ONE LEAKING CARTON AND THE ONE CARTON THAT THE MATERIAL SPILLED ON INTO A CONTAINMENT BARRELL.  I THEN WENT OFF DUTY  FOR 2 DAYS.  IN MY ABSENCES THE TWO CONTAMINATED CARTONS WERE SHIPPED TO THE ULTIMATE CONSIGNEE. AFTER RECEIVED ASSURANCES FROM THE SHIPPER THAT THE SHIPMENT CONTAINED NO DANGEROUS GOODS.  WHEN THE SHIPPER FINALLY FAXED THE "MSDS" IT WAS FOUND TO CONTAIN A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL UN1760. (TROXYMITE). CORRECTIVE ACTION TAKEN INCLUDES A NEW PROCEDURE OF HOLDING ALL QUESTIONABLE SHIPMENTS UNTIL THE "MSDS" IS IN HAND, IN ADDITON TO FOLLOWING ALL THE ESTABLISHED PROCEDURES OF HANDLING AND SHIPPING DG SHIPMENTS.

column168: I WAS GOING EAST ON THE OHIO TOLL ROAD AT THE 109 MARKER AND HEARD ON THE CBCHANNEL #19 THAT TRAFFIC WAS BACKING UP FAST IN BOTH LANES AT THE EXIT FOR HWY#4. I LOOKED AHEADREAL QUICK & BOTH LANES HAD NOTHING BUT CARS WITH RED LIGHTS ON. AS THE GUARDRAIL ENDED I MOVED TO THE GRAVEL WITH MY COMPLETE RIGHT ON THE GRAVEL. I LOOKEDBACK IN MY LEFT DRIVER DOOR MIRROR & VEH #2 MOVED TO THE SLOW LANE THEN  I SAWTRAFFIC IN FRONT OF VEH #1 & FURTHER PAST ME. VEH #2 THEN STEERED HARD TO THELEFT TO AVOID HITTING ME IN THE REAR. AND THE COIL CAME OFF THE MIDDLE OF THEFLATBED & I (VEH #1) SAW THE COIL COMING AND STAYED ON THE EMERENCY SHOULDER TOAVOID HITTING  THE CARS STOPPED IN THE RIGHT SLOW LANE. THE DRIVER WAS MAKING A DELIVERY TO A RE-ACQUIRED FLEET ACCOUNT. THE COMPANY, OVERNITE TRANSPORTATION, HAD REPLACED IT'S UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANKS WITH ONE ABOVE GROUND. MOBIL WAS TOLD THAT THIS TANK HAD A 12000 GALLON STORAGE CAPACITY. THE DRIVER HAVING DETERMINED THE LOAD WOULD FIT, STARTED TO PUMP INTO THE TANK. JUST AT THE CARGO TANK WAS EMPTYING, THE PRODUCE BEGAN TO SPRAY OUT OF THE TOP OF THE ABOVE GROUND STORAGE TANK. THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY CLOSED DOWN THE DISCHCARGE VALVE TO STOP THE FLOW, THEN SHUT DOWN THE PUMP. THE SPILLED FUEL RAN DOWN THE SIDES OF THE TANK AND THE STEEL CONTAINMENT STRUCTURE ON TO THE CONCRETE PAD BELOW. SOME OF THE PRODUCT MIGRATED OFF THE EDGE OF THE PAD AND STAINED THE STONE ON EACH SIDE OF THE TANK. WE LEARNED LATER THAT IN FACT THIS ABOVE GROUND TANK WAS A 10000/GALLON, NOT A 12000/GAL. THE STONE WAS CLEANED UP THE FOLLOWING DAY AND REPLACED WITH A NEW STONE. THIS BEING A DIESEL OR DISTILLATE FUEL, A NON HAZARDOUS WASTE MANIFEST WAS USED TO TRANSPORT THE STONE FOR DISPOSAL. DEC NOTIFIED.

A FREIGHT LOADER AT THE ORGIN TERMINAL HAD PLACED A HAVY SKID OF FREIGHT ON TOP OF THE PAILS AS HE WAS LOADING THE OUTBOUND TRAILER.  THE WEIGHT OF THE SKID ON TOP OF THE PAILS CAUSED ONE PAIL TO BECOM CRUSHED ON ONE SIDE AT THE TOP.  THE CRIMPING OF THE METAL CAUSED A SMALL TEAR ON THE SIDE OF THE PAIL NEAR THE TOP RELEASING APPROXIMATELY ONE GALLON OF LIQUID WHICH EVAPORATED.   PAIL TRANSFERRED TO OS & D FOR FURTHER HANDLING.  DOCK PERSONNEL SHOULD BE AWARE OF THE SKID FRIEGHT WHICH IS PLACED ON TOP OF PAILS IN A TRAILER.  ONLY LIGHT SKID FRIEGHT SHOULD BE LOADED ON TOP OF PAILS.

column168: FOUR PAILS LOCATED AT THE BOTTOM LAYER OF THE PALLET MOVED SLIGHTLY OFF THE PALLET DURING TRANSIT. PRESSURE FROM THE TOP PAILS CAUSED BOTTOM RIMS TO BECOME DENTED. WRAPPING AROUND BOTTOM OF THE PALLET WAS NOT SECURED ENOUGH TO PREVENT MOVEMENT OF PAILS. IN ADDITION,  LOAD LOCK AGAINST THE PALLET TO PREVENT MOVEMENT OF FREIGHT WAS NOT SECURED TIGHT ENOUGH AND FELL DURING TRANSIT. FOUR PAILS FROM A SHIPMENT OF TEN (10) CONSIGNED TO VASCO INC, PADUCAH, KY, WERE REFUSED BY THE CONSIGNEE DUE TO THREE PAILS BEING DENTED AND ONE PAIL LEAKING. THE DRIVER LFET THE PAILS ON THE TRAILER AND NOTIFIED THE CARRIER WHEN HE ARRIVED AT HIS LAST STOP AT CLAYTON INDUSTRIES, ALBIENE, TX. THE CUSTOMER IN ALBIENE, TX., ACCEPTED THE FOUR PAILS THAT WERE DAMAGED. THE ONE CONTAINER WHICH LEAKED, ONLY LEAKED IN THE TRAILER. NO EXPOSURE TO THE ENVIRONMENT. TRAILER WSA DECONTAMINATED IN ALBIENE, TX. SHIPPER IS TO PROVIDE TIGHTER WRAPPING ON FUTURE SHIPMENTS. DRIVER ADVISED TO REPORT INCIDENT WHEN DISCOVERED AND CHECK LOAD LOCKS FOR SECUREMENT IN THE FUTURE.

column168: A VAN TRAILER CONTAINING HAZARDOUS WASTE WAS ENROUTE FROM CLEAN HARBORS OF BALTIMORE, INC. LOCATED AT 1910 RUSSELL STREET IN BALTIMORE, MD TO THERMALKEM, INC. LOCATED AT 2324 VERNESDALE ROAD IN ROCK HILL, SC. DURING THE COURSE OF THE TRIP, THE DRIVER MADE A ROUTINE STOP TO CONDUCT A TIRE AND LOAD CHECK AND DISCOVEREED THAT APPROXIMATELY 5 GALLONS OF MATERIAL HAD FROM THE TOP LID OF A CONTAINER WHICH HAD OVERTURNED IN TRANSIT. THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED THE RELEASE WITH SPEEDI DRY AND CONTACTED HIS DISPATCHER WHO DISPATCHED A CLEAN-UP CREW TO THE SCENE. UPON ARRIVAL AT THE SCENE, THE CLEAN-UP CREW ABSORBED ALL FREE LIQUIDS WITH SPEEDI DRY, OVERPACKED THE DAMAGED CONTAINER INTO A SUITABLE SALVAGE DRUM AND CONTAINERIZED ALL CLEAN UP DEBRIS FOR DISPOSAL. THE CREW NOTED THAT THE BLOCKING AND BRACING SYSTEM USED TO SECURE THE CONTAINERS HAD FAILED. IT WAS ALSO DISCOVERED THAT THE GASKET USED AS A SEAL BETWEEN THE DRUM BODY AND THE CLOSURE WAS NOT SEATED PROPERLY. THIS ALLOWED THE MATERIAL TO ESCAPE WHEN THE DRUM OVERTURNED. AS A RESULT OF THIS INCIDENT, 2 X 55 GALLON DRUMS OF CONTAMINATED PPE AND ABSORBENT MATERIAL WERE GENERATED ALONG WITH THE DRUM THAT WAS PLACED INTO THE SALVAGE CONTAINER. THIS MATERIAL WAS MANIFESTED AND SENT FOR DISPOSAL TO CLEAN HARBORS OF BALTIMORE, INC. LOCATED AT 1910 RUSSELL STREET IN BALTIMORE, MD. IN ORDER TO PREVENT A RECURRENCE OF THIS INCIDENT, DRIVERS AND LOADING PERSONNEL HAVE BEEN RE-INSTRUCTED TO INSURE THAT ALL CONTAINERS ARE PROPERLY SECURED PRIOR TO LOADING. IN ADDITION, ALL LOADING PERSONNEL WILL ENSURE THAT ADEQUATE BLOCKING AND BRACING IS UTILIZED TO SECURE EACH LOAD.

A VAN TRAILER CONTAINING HAZARDOUS WASTE WAS ENROUTE FROM ALLIED COLLOIDS, LOCATED AT 2301 MILROY ROAD IN SUFFOLK, VA SPRING GROVE RESOURCE RECOVERY, INC. LOCATED AT 4879 SPRING GROVE AVENUE IN CINCINNATI, OH. DURING A ROUTINE STOP AT CLEAN HARBOR'S CLEVELAND SERVICE CENTER LOCATED AT 2940 INDEPENDENCE ROAD IN CLEVELAND, OH APPROXIMATELY 1 GALLON OF MATERIAL ESCAPED FROM THE TOP LID OF ONE OF THE CONTAINERS ONTO THE CONCRETE PARKING AREA WHEN THE CONTAINER WAS BEING TRANSFERRED TO ANOTHER VEHICLE FOR CONTINUING TRANSPORT. FACILITY PERSONNEL IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED THE RELEASE WITH SPEEDI DRY AND OVERPACKED THE LEAKING CONTAINER INTO A SUITABLE SALVAGE DRUM ALONG WITH ALL CLEAN-UP DEBRIS FOR TRANSPORTATION TO THE WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY LISTED ON THE SHIPPING DOCUMENT. IT IS BELIEVED THAT THE GASKET ACTING AS A SEAL BETWEEN THE DRUM BODY AND THE CLOSURE WAS DEFECTIVE ALLOWING THE MATERIAL TO ESCAPE. PRIOR TO DEPARTURE FROM THE SHIPPER'S LOCATION, THE LOAD WAS INSPECTED AND NO EVIDENCE OF LEAKING OR DAMAGE WAS OBSERVED. ALL DRIVERS AND LOADING PERSONNEL WILL CONTINUE TO INSPECT EACH CONTAINER AS IT IS LOADED AND TO TAKE APPROPRIATE ACTIONS IN THE EVENT A CONTAINER IS FOUND NOT TO BE STRUCTURALLY SOUND.

TRUCK AND TRAILER WERE PICKED UP AT THE  HARDING ST ADDRESS OF THE HILL AND GRIFFITH COMPANY AT 7:30 PM ON JULY 4, 1995. AT 10;00 PM THE  TRUCK DRIVEN BY  ROBERT SOPHER ARRIVED AT THE GALLAHAN TRUCK STOP LOCATED IN PERU, INDIANA ON US  31. THE DRIVER THEN WALKED AROUND HIS TRUCK AND INSPECTED IT. HE NOTICED MATERIAL LEAKING FROM THE TRAILER. HE OPENED THE BACK DOORS AND SAW THAT THE PLASTIC DRUMS HAD FALLED AND WERE NO  LONGER ON THE PALLET. HE THEN WENT INSIDE THE TRUCK STOP AND NOTIFIED  THE ATTENDANT AND CALLED CHEMTREC. CHEMTREC TOLD MR SOPHER TO CALL THE FIRE DEPARTMENT, WHICH HE DID. HE ALSO CALLED HIS IMMEDIATE SUPERVISOR, JERRY STANLEY. THE VOLUNTEER FIRE DEPARTMENT ARRIVED UNDER THE DIRECTION OF MR. COMERFORD AND CONTAINED THE SPILL. INDIANA STATE POLICEMAN ARRIVED AT THE SCENE AND REVIEWED DRIVER'S LOG AND PAPERWORK. DOT HAZARDOUS MATERIALS OFFICER FROM LOGANSPORT, INDIANA WAS ALSO CALLED TO THE SCENE TO INVESTIGATE THE SPILL. LORI R YEAGER, CORPORATE GOVERNMENT REGULATORY MANAGER, WAS NOTIFIED BY JERRY STANLEY, SHIPPING SUPERVISOR. MS. YEAGER SPOKE WITH FIRE DEPARTMENT, IDEM. SPILL RECOVERY OF INDIANA ARRIVED AT SCENE AT 2AM. SCENE NEUTRALIZED BY 5AM SPILL RECOVERY OF INDIANA WAS CALLED BY MS YEAGER AND ORIGINATED OUT OF INDIANAPOLIS, INDIANA. SPILL RECOVERY SENT TWO TRUCKS AND FOUR INDIVIDUALS. THE HAZ MAT PEOPLE NEUTRALIZED THE ACID BOTH ON THE GROUND AND IN THE TRAILER WITH SODA ASH. THE PUNCTURED DRUM WAS PLACED IN AN OVERPACK. ALL MATERIALS WERE THEN RELOADED AND STRAIGHTENED ON THE PALLET. LOADLOCK WAS THEN SECURED. DRIVER RETURNED TO HILL AND GRIFFITH WAREHOUSE AND RINSE TRAILER. FUTURE ACTION TO PREVENT SUCH INCIDENTS FROM REOCCURING IS TO PURCHASE STRAPS FOR DRIVERS. THUS, EVEN THOUGH DRUMS ARE SHRINKWRAPPED, THEY  WILL STAY IN PLACE. PLEASE NOT-QUESTION 35 ON PAGE TWO OF THE REPORT WAS ANSWERED AS MANUFACTURED DATE, BECAUSED THE DAMAGED DRUM IS IN THE OVERPACK. WE DID NOT WANT TO EXPOSE OUR EMPLOYEES TO THE ACID TO DETERMINE THE MARKINGS. THIS ACID BLEND IS MANUFACTURED  FOR US BY VAN WATERS AND ROGERS. VAN WATERS AND ROGERS PACKAGES THE MATERIAL FOR US. WE PICK IT UP FROM THEM AND SELL IT UNDER OUR NAME. QUESTION 39B WAS ANSWERED IN THAT FASHION, BECAUSE THE DRUMS ARE TESTED AS REQUIRED BY DOT REGULATIONS AND ARE DEPENDENT ON THE AGE OF THE DRUM.

OUR LOGEX DRIVER HAD JUST ARRIVED AT RIVER OAKS HOSPITAL AND WENT INSIDE TO CHECK IN AND USE THE TELEPHONE. OUR DRIVER CAME OUT AFTER SEVERAL MINUTES AND FOUND LIQUID OXYGEN FLOWING FROM A LIQUID SAMPLE LINE. THE LIQUID SAMPLE LINE BROKE AT A MECHANICAL JOINT. THE STAINLESS STEEL TUBING THAT IS ATTACHED TO A LIQUID LINE AT A SWAGELOK FITTING WHICH EVENTUALLY LEADS TO THE PRESSURE BUILDING COIL BROKE. THE LINE CARRIES ABOUT 10 POUNDS OF PRESSURE. THE PRESSURE IN THE TRAILER WAS VENTED AND THE SAMPLE LINE WAS CAPPED, THE TRAILER WAS THEN OFF-LOADED WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT. THE TRAILER WAS TAKEN BACK TO THE SHOP AND THE SAMPLE LINE REPAIRED. THE TRAILER WAS INSPECTED THOROUGHLY AND IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE TRAILER WAS FINE EXCEPT FOR THE BREAK IN THE STAINLESS STEEL TUBING.

VEHICLE THEN LEFT THE ROAD AND HIT THE SIDE OF A MOUNTAIN. DRIVER AND CO-DRIVER WERE INJURED AND TAKEN TO HOSPITAL. WE HAD 211 CARTONS OF HM LOAD, AMONG OTHER FREIGHT THAT WERE NOT HM COMMODITY. CHP, AMBULANCES, AND KERN ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICE WERE AT THE SCENE IN A MATTER OF MINUTES. CLEAN UP OF CONTAMINATED SOIL WAS DONE AND PUT IN METAL STORAGE BINS AND TRANSPORTED TO A HAZARDOUS WASTE DISPOSAL SITE. SHIPMENT WAS PLACARDED AT TIME OF PICKUP. POLICE REPORT SAYS IT WAS NOT AT TIME OF ACCIDENT. SOMEWHERE BETWEEN CINCINNATI AND SCENE OF ACCIDENT THE PLACARDS DISAPPEARED. ALL OF OUR NEW HIRES ARE PUT THROUGH A SAFETY AWARENESS PROGRAM, ALONG WITH A HAZ MAT TRAINING PROGRAM CALLED HM-126 F. WE ARE CURRENTLY GIVING ALL DRIVERS A REFRESHER COURSE ON BOTH SUBJECTS TO MAKE THEM BETTER AWARE.

EMPLOYEE RECEIVED IMMEDIATE MEDICAL ATTENTION.  BURLINGTON NORTHERN HAZARDOUS MATERIAL RESPONDERS AND SHIPPER WERE NOTIFIED.  INSPECTION OF THE CAR REVEALED A TEAR IN THE MANWAY GASKET. A SWITCH CREW DISCOVERED TANK CAR NATX 38571, DENATURED ALCOHOL, 3, NA1987,  PG 11 LEAKING FROM A TOP FITTING.  THE AREA BUREAU OF EXLOSIVES INSPECTOR WAS NOTIFIED.  INSPECTION OF THE CAR REVEALED THAT THERE WAS NOT A LIQUID TIGHT SEAL WHERE THE BALL VALVE ATTACHES TO THE TOP OF THE 3-INCH LIQUID DISCHARGE LINE.  DUE TO THE HIGH AMBIENT TEMPERATURE, INCREASED PRESSURE IN THE VAPOR SPACE INSIDE THE TANK FORCES LADING THROUGH THE LIQUID DISCHARGE LINE AND THE DEFECTIVE CONNECTION BETWEEN THE DISCHARGE LINE AND VALVE.  AFTER THE INTERNAL TANK PRESSURE WAS RELIEVED, THE LIQUID VALVE WAS REMOVED, THREAD TAPE APPLIED TO THE DISCHARGE LINE THREADS, AND THE LIQUID VALVE REINSTALLED, PROPERLY SEALING THE CONNECTION.  THE CAR WAS THEN RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT TO DESTINATION.

FURTHER INSPECTION REVEALED THAT A 330 GALLON PORTABLE TANK HAD FAILED ALLOWING APPROXIMATELY 225 GALLON OF REFRIDGERANT OIL TO BE RELEASED INSIDE OF TRAILER.  THE RELEASE WAS CAUSED BY A FORKLIFT CREASING THE DIE OF TANK WHICH LATER FAILED WHILE IN TRANSIT.  SPILLED MATERIAL WAS CONTAINED INSIDE TRAILER ON STEEL SECONDARY CONTAINMENT PAN, HOWEVER 10 TO 15 GALLONS DID COME OVER TOP OF TAILGATE AND SPILL ONTO DISPOSAL FACILITY LOT.  THIS WAS CLEANED BY TSD PERSONNEL. THE TRAILER WAS OFFLOADED AND SPILLED MATERIAL RECOVERED AND PLACED INTO RECOVERY DRUMS.  TRAILER FLOOR WAS DECONTAMINATED BY TSDF PERSONNEL. TELEPHONE REPORTS WERE MADE TO THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER (REPORT NO. 298795) ALABAMA EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT, ALABAMA DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT, AND THE DEPARTMENT OF PUBLIC SAFETY.  NO FURTHER PROBLEMS ARE ENCOUNTERED.

AT APPROXIMATELY 1800 ON THURSDAY JULY 20, 1995 AN N&M TRANFER DOCKMAN WAS LOADING TRAILER 546 WHILE IT WAS UP AGAINST A DOOR IN THE SOUTH DOCK. THE DOCKMAN ENTERED THE TRAILER UNAWARE THAT HIS FORKS WERE PROTRUDING FROM THE PALLET HE WAS LOADING ON TO THIS TRAILER.  THE DOCKMAN SET THE SKID DOWN RIGHT BEHIND ANOTHER SKID OF PAILS.  HE WAS NOT AWARE THAT THE TWO FORKS FROM HIS TOWMOTOR HAD PUNCTURED THE VERY BOTTOM RIM OF (2) FIVE GALLON PAILS OF A CLASS 6.1 POISON (HERBICIDE).  THE DOCKMAN IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED HIS DOCK SUPERVISOR WHO THEN  NOTIFIED OUR TERMINAL OFFICE. AFTER THE NIGHT BILLING SUPERVISOR RECEIVED THE CALL HE IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED (CHEMTREC)  AND THEY FAXED A COPY OF THE MSDS TO OUR TERMINAL OFFICE. AFTER THE EMERGENCY INFORMATION WAS RECIVED, DOCK FOREMAN EVACUATED THE IMMEDIATE AREA.  PERSONNNAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT (SUITS AND SCBA'A ) WERE USED BY OUT FOREMAN IN THE CLEAN UP.  WASTE FROM THE CLEAN UP IS BEING DISPOSED OF THROUGH OUR HAZARDOUS WASTE COMPANY.  THE TRAILER WAS TAKEN TO A LOCAL TANK WAS FOR DECONTAMINATION.  THE DOCKMAN RESPONSIBLE FOR THE SPILL RECEIVED A ONE DAY SUSPENSION FOR IMPROPER LOADING.
CUSTOMER TANK OVERFLOWED WHEN DRIVER WAS FILLING.  SITE GAUGE NOT WORKING. CUSTOMER CLEANED UP SPILL.
HOSES WERE CAPPED AND IN TROUGH ON TRAILER.  ONE CAP CAME LOOSE AND PRODUCT CAME OUT.  CLEANED UP WITH ABSORBANT.

HUKILL CHEMICAL CORPORATION (HCC) DRIVER DELIVERED 750 GALLONS OF SULFURIC ACID, 66 TO AMERICAN METALS IN WESTLAKE,OH. MATERIAL WAS DELIVERED IN MC312 TRANSPORT CARGO TANK, AND PRESSURE UNLOADED TO AMERICAN METALS' 1000 GAL., HORIZONTAL, ELEVATED STORAGE TANK. AT COMPLETION OF UNLOADING, DRIVER WAS BEGINNING DISCONNECT SEQUENCE, AND CUSTOMER'S STORAGE TANK RUPTURED, WITH ONE TANK HEAD FAILING ACROSS APPROX. 180 DEGREE OF THE HEAD'S CIRCUMFERENCE, FROM APPROX. 12 O'CLOCK POSITION TO 6 O'CLOCK POSITION. SULFURIC ACID FROM RUPTURED TANK SPLASHED LOCAL BUILDING SIDING, AND DRAINED TO TANK CONTAINMENT AREA, LOCAL CONCRETE OUTSIDE OF CONTAINMENT, AND EARTHEN AREA ADJACENT TO CONCRETE. IMMEDIATE RESPONSE BY PLAT PERSONNEL CONSISTED OF NOTIFICATION OF LOCAL EMERGENCY RESPONSE PERSONNEL. WESTLAKE FIRE DEPARTMENT AND WESTSHORE HAZMAT TEAM RESPONDED WITHIN 5-10 MINUTES (EST). THEY EVACUATED ON-SITE PERSONNEL TO A SAFE DISTANCE WITHIN THE PLANT, AND STOPPED MOVEMENT OF MATERIAL BY DAMMING WITH NEUTRALIZING AGENT (SODA ASH).

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Improper Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: DRIVER STATED THAT HE SIGNED FOR AND PICKED UP 54 BOXES CONTAINING 50 CHARGES IN EACH BOX.  AFTER STACKING THE BOXES ON TWO PALLETS HE TOOK SOME SHRINK WRAP AND WRAPPED EACH UNTIL SECURE.  HE RAN A STRAP ACROSS THEM AND DEPARTED.  WHEN THE DRIVER CROSSED THE TRACKS HE SAW SOME BOXES FALL AND IMMEDIATELY PULLED OVER STOPPED.  A MAN IN A HALLIBURTON TRUCK PULLED OVER ON THE LEFT SHOULDER OF THE STREET AND STARTED TO ASSIST THE DRIVER IN PICKING UP THE BOXES.  ANOTHER MAN IN A HALLIBURTON STATION WAGON PULLED IN FRONT OF OUR TRUCK AND ALSO ASSISTED.  WHILE COLLECTING RESTACKING THE BOXES HE NOTICED ONE OF THE MEN WALKING BACK FROM THE CAR.  OUR DRIVER BELIEVED HE HAD COLLECTED ALL OF THE BOXES AND LOOSE CHARGES, THANKED THEM FOR THE HELP, AND RETURNED TO THE ACME TERMINAL IN LAFAYETTE.  HE TARPED AND SECURED THE LOAD AND PROCEEDED HARVEY.  UPON ARRIVAL, OUR DRIVER COUNTED THE SHIPMENT SEVERAL TIMES AND CAME UP WITH 50 BOXES AND THREE BAGS (INNER PACKAGING) OF CHARGES.  HE DISCOVERED AT THIS TIME THAT ONE OF THE PLASTIC BAGS WAS TORN WITH ONE CHARGE MISSING.  AN EXTENSIVE SEARCH WAS THEN MADE OF THE AREA WHERE THE BOXES FELL.  ONE CHARGE WAS FOUND AND RETURNED.  AN ATTEMPT WAS MADE TO RECOUNT THE BOXES AT THE DESTINATION, BUT SOME WERE ALREADY GONE AND USED.  THERE ARE THREE POSSIBLE SCENARIOS WHICH COULD EXPLAIN THE ABOVE.  FIRST, A MISCOUNT MAY HAVE OCCURRED AT THE INCEPTION OF THE HAUL, I.E., 53 BOXES COULD HAVE BEEN PICKED UP INSTEAD OF 54.  SECONDLY, THE BOXES COULD HAVE BEEN MISCOUNTED AT THE DESTINATION. FINALLY, ONE BOX POSSIBLY BE MISSING, ALTHOUGH IT WAS NOT PRESENT AT THE SCENE WHEN THE SCENE WAS RECHECKED FOLLOWING THE INCIDENT. BECAUSE THE SHIPMENT WAS PARTIALLY USED AFTER IT WAS DELIVERED, THERE IS NO WAY AT THIS TIME TO VERIFY EXACTLY WHICH SCENARIO IS CORRECT.  ALTHOUGH IT IS IMPOSSIBLE TO COMPLETELY PREVENT AN INCIDENT SUCH AS THIS ONE, ACME WILL INTRODUCE STEPS TO ATTEMPT TO LESSEN THE RISK OF A FUTURE SIMILAR OCCURRENCE.  ACME WILL RE-EMPHASIZE TO ITS DRIVERS THE NECESSITY OF CORRECTLY UTILIZING TARPS AND SIDEBOARDS WITH APPROPRIATE LOADS, AND WILL, AGAIN, EMPHASIZE THE NEED FOR COMPLETE COMPLIANCE WITH ACMES INCIDENT NOTIFICATIONS PROCEDURES.

DRIVER DISCOVERED LEAKAGE FROM TRAILER AS HE WAS PREPARING TO UNLOAD.  TWO DRUMS ON THE REAR OF THE TRAILER HAD FALLEN OVER AND LEAKED PRODUCT.  HE CALLED GREEN FIELD'S SAFETY DEPARTMENT AS PER COMPANY PROCEDURE.  GREEN FIELD NOTIFIED THE PHILADELPHIA RESPONSE HAZMAT CENTER.  A RESPONSE TEAM WAS DISPATCHED TO THE SCENE, AND THE SCENE WAS SECURED.  AT THE REQUEST OF THE RESPONSE TEAM, A HAZMAT CLEANUP COMPANY WAS NOTIFIED BY GREEN FIELD AND ALSO DISPATCHED TO THE SCENE TO CLEAN THE SITE.  THE SCENE WAS CLEANED AND THE REMAINDER OF THE PRODCUT WAS DECONTAMINATED, PRIOR TO DELIVERY, AND THE TRAILER WAS DECONTAMINATED WHEN EMPTY.  THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER WAS NOTIFIED BY GREEN FIELD ON 7/13/95 AFTER THE SCENE WAS CLEARED.  THE NATIONAL RESPONSE REPORT #29661.  THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED AT THE OCCURANCE OF THE PROBLEM.  COMMUNICATIONS BETWEEN THE RESPONSE CENTER, S & D ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES AND GREEN FIELD WERE UPDATED APPROX. EVERY HOUR.

FOUND DRUM IN FRONT ONE THIRD OF TRAILER WITH PRODUCT COVERING FLOOR OF TRAILER-THE CONTAINER WAS ALMOST COMPLETELY EMPTY WHEN GOT TO IT. THERE IS A CRACK IN BOTTOM EDGE OF DRUM, 4 INCHES LONG. THE DRUM HAD NO OUTSIDE ACTION CAUSING THE FAILURE. THE DRUM GIVES NO INDICATION OF IMPACT OR FORCE ANYWHERE AROUND THE FAILED AREA OF DRUM. THE DRUM WAS A STC (SINGLE TRIP CONTAINER) DRUM WITH MANUFACTURER DATE OF 1993. THE DRUM APPEARS TO HAVE BEEN USED PRIOR TO THIS TRIP.

JERRY SHORT WAS ATTEMPTING TO UNLOAD A TRUCK FROM SAFETY KLEEN, CLARKSVILLE. THE MATERIAL IN THE BOTTOM OF THE TRUCK WAS A THICK SAND LIKE MATERIAL. THE HOSE BECAME FULL OF THIS MATERIAL AND FLOW FROM THE TRAILER CEASED. FOLLOWING STANDARD PROCEDURES, JERRY ATTEMPTED TO BLOW THROUGH THE LINE, BACK INTO THE TRUCK, WITH NITROGEN. DURING THIS PROCEDURE, THE BANDING HOLDING THE CAMLOCK IN THE END OF THE HOSE CAME LOOSE. THE CAMLOCK CAME FREE OF THE HOSE AND THE MATERIAL IN THE HOSE SPRAYED ONTO THE TRUCK PAD AND GRAVEL IN FRONT OF THE TRUCK PAD. JERRY IMMEDIATELY SHUT OFF THE NITROGEN AND CLOSED THE UNLOADING VALVE ON THE TRUCK. SCOTT GRIFFITH WAS NOTIFIED AND CLEAN UP BEGAN. THE GRAVEL WAS PICKED UP USING THE BOBCAT AND SHOVELS. MATERIAL ON THE TRUCK PAD WAS PICKED UP USING ABSORBENT PADS, AND LACQUER THINNER. THE ENTIRE AREA WAS CLEANED UP IN APPROXIMATELY THREE HOURS. SCOTT GRIFFITH CALLED ROB TURNER AND DAN HOLDNACK IMMEDIATELY AFTER THE INITIAL RELEASE. DAN HOLDNACK RETURNED SCOTT'S CALL AT APPROXIMATELY 3:00 P.M. A TOTAL OF 58.5 POUNDS OF MATERIAL WAS RELEASED ONTO THE TRUCK PAD AND THE GRAVEL. APPROXIMATELY 2/3 REMAINED ON THE TRUCK PAD AND 1/3 WAS ON THE GRAVEL.

VEHICLE WAS A SEMI-END DUMP WITH TARP.

column168: SCHNEIDER NATIONAL DRIVER NOTICED PRODUCT LEAKING OUT OF HIS TRAILER. WHILE OVERPACKING THE NON-HAZMAT DRUM, THEY NOTICED THE ONE HAZMAT DRUM "WEEPING". HAZMAT TEAM LEADER GENE DITTER DESCRIBED THIS AS AN "INHERENT PROBLEM WITH PLASTIC DRUMS" AND THAT THE DRUM "HAD PRODUCT ON THE OUTSIDE, NEAR THE BOTTOM BUT NOT ENOUGH TO FORM A PUDDLE". HE OBSERVED PRODUCT ACTUALLY "WEEPING" OUT OF THE HAZMAT DRUM. THE HAZMAT TEAM TEAM TESTED THE MATERIAL ON THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER AND GROUND AND NOTED THAT IT WAS NOT ACIDIC.

LOCAL DRIVER WAS DELIVER ON HIS ROUTE. THE DEWAR WAS NOT PROPERLY BLOCKED IN HIS TRAILER AND AS HE WENT UP A HILL THE DEWAR FELL OVER. THE IMPACT OF THE DEWAR HITTING THE TRAILER FLOOR CAUSED ONE OF THE VALVES TO OPEN PARTIALLY RELEASING SOME HELIUM. THE DRIVER WAS ABLE TO SHUT THE VALVE OFF AND UPRIGHT THE DEWAR TO ITS ORIGINAL POSITION. DRIVER DELIVERED THE DEWAR WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT. THE DRIVER WAS TOLD TO PROPERLY BLOCK FUTURE HAZ MAT SHIPMENTS TO HIS TRAILER.

THE SALVAGE DRUM WAS RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER FOR CLAIM CREDIT. THE BALANCE OF THE SHIPMENT WAS FORWARDED TO DESTINATION. THE SPILLAGE HAD EVAPORTED. THE TRAILER WAS CLEANED UP FOR REUSE.

THE LAIDLAW DRIVER PICKED UP  5 WRANGLERS AT E.T.&L CONSTRUCTION CORP,. GLENDALE ROAD, NORTHAMPTON, MA WHICH CONTAINED HAZARDOUS WASTE SOLID, N.O.S. (METHYL ETHYL KETONE, INK PIGMENTS) HAZ CLASS 9, NA3077, PAGIII. THE DRIVER NOTICED THAT 1 WRANGLER WAS LEAKING WHEN HE ARRIVED AT HIS NEXT STOP. THE CONTAINER HAD BEEN STORED OUTSIDE AND WAS FILLED WITH RAIN WATER. HE THEN POURED 2 BAGS OF SPEEDI-DRY ON THE MATERIAL THAT HAD LEAKED OUT. THE SPEEDI DRY WAS PUT INTO TO THE WRANGLER ONCE THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP. THE DRIVER WAS GIVEN INSTRUCTIONS TO CONTINUE ONHIS ROUTE AND TO CHECK LEAK PERIODICALLY. WHEN HE RETURNED TO LAIDLAW ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES (NORTH EAST), INC., 300 CANAL STREET, LAWRENCE, MA THE WRANGLER WAS OVERPACKED INTO A SUPER SACK CONTAINER AND SHIPPED TO AN END DISPOSAL FACILITY.

THE DRIVER WAS PREPARING TO UNLOAD A BIN OF HAZARDOUS WASTE SOLID AT US ECOLOGY, THE DISPOSAL FACILITY. HE LOOSENED THE BIN DOOR CLOSURE MECHANISM. WHILE MOVING THE BIN IN THE STAGING AREA, APPROXIMATELY 1/2 YARD OF THE MATERIAL SPILLED ONTO THE GROUND. THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS SCOOPED BACK INTO THE BIN BY US ECOLOGY EARTH MOVING EQUIPMENT. THE DRIVER HAS BEEN COUNSELED ON THE PROPER PROCEDURE FOR UNLOADING ROLL-OFF BINS.

DRIVER NOTICED VAPOR UNDER PUMPING CABINET. DRIVER STOPPED AT REST STOP AND NOTIFIED TERMINAL. TERMINAL DISPATCHED MECHANICS TO SCENE. PIPING TO ROAD RELIEF VALVE FOUND CRACKED. TRAILER PLACED ON ALTERNATE SAEFTY AND TRANSPORTED APPROXIMATELY 30 MILES TO TERMINAL WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT. TRAILER PIPING REPAIRED. ALL TRAILERS IN THIS SERIES INSPECTED FOR SIMILAR PROBLEM. ROOT CAUSE: ROAD VIBRATION.

CONSIGNEE WAS PREPARING TO UNLOAD TANK CAR. THE TOP FITTINGS ON THE CAR WERE NOT COMPATIBLE WITH THE UNLAODING ARM. FITTINGS WERE ADAPTED, AND THE UNLOADING ARM WAS CONNECTED TO THE CAR. WHEN THE VALVE WAS CRACKED TO BEGIN UNLOADING, THE VAPOR PRESSURE IN THE CAR FORCED PRODUCT UP THE PIPE. PRODUCT THEN WAS OBSERVED LEAKING FROM THE THREADS ON THE ADAPTOR FITTING. SPILL WAS CONTAINED WITH ABSORBANT PADS. CORRECTIVE ACTION: COMMUNICATE FAULTY FITTINGS TO SHIPPER. ORDER NECESSARY FITTINGS FOR HOOKUP USING HILTAP.

LOADER HAD TO RADIO UPSTAIRS TO HAVE THEM CUT IT OFF. THEY STOPPED AND TANK HAD NOT OVERFLOWED. THE SHIPPER THEN BLEW THEIR LINES OUT CAUSING CENTRAL TRAILER TO OVERFLOW.

THERE WAS A DRIPPING LEAK AT THE BOTTOM OF THE PRODUCT PUMP. THERE WAS BSORBANT AND A BUCKET UNDER THE LEAK SO NOTHING WOULD GET ON THE GROUND. AT APPROACH TO TOLL PLAZA DRIVER WAS CUT OFF BY ANOTHER MOTORIST AND HAD TO SLAM ON BRAKES TO AVOID HITTING OTHER VEHICLE.  WHEN DRIVER APPLIED BRAKES HARD, ONE OF THE CYLINDERS IN TH EVAN FELL OVER AND THE VALVE ON THE TOP OF THE CYLINDER BROKE WHEN IT HIT THE FLOOR OF THE VAN.  DRIVER PULLED OVER TO THE SIDE OF ROADWAY AND CHECKED INSIDE VEHICLE AND FOUND NO LEAKS.  UPON CHECKING VEHICLE AGAIN APPROXIMATELY 30 MINUTES LATER, HE FOUND THAT CYLINDER HAD BEGUN TO LEAK.  DRIVER PLACED ABSORBANT ON ROADWAY TO ABSORB SPILLED MATERIAL.  ILLINOIS HIGHWAY PATROL ARRIVED ON SCENE AND STAYED WITH VEHICLE UNTIL ASSISTANCE ARRIVED TO UPRIGHT THE CYLINDER. CYLINDER INTERMITTENTLY LEAKED A SMALL QUANTITY DURNIG INCIDENT. ONCE UPRIGHT VALVE WAS ABLE TO BE REPAIRED TO STOP/PREVENT FURTHER LEAKAGE. MEMBER OF ILLINOIS HAZMAT TEAM ARRIVED ON SCENE, SURVEILLED AREA, AND FELT ATHAT THE SITUATION WAS UNDER CONTROL SO DID NOT PROVIDE FURTHER RESPONSE. ABSORBENT WAS CLEANED UP AND TRANSPORTED TO CONSIGNEE WHO TOOK POSSESSION OF THE MATERIAL FOR DISPOSAL.  DRIVER ADJUSTED LOAD LOCKS PRIOR TO DEPARTURE. OTHER CONTAINERS IN SHIPMENT WERE NOT DAMAGED DURING INCIDENT.

column168: THE DRIVER INSPECTED HIS TRUCK AND LOAD IN FRANKLIN LA.  A RACK CONTAINING OXYGEN AND ACETYLENE BOTTLES WAS PART OF HIS SHIPMENT.  THE RACK WAS SECURED TO THE FLAT BED WITH A CHAIN AND BINDER.  HE STOPPED IN SCHRIEVER, LA. TO RE-CHECK THE LOAD.  FOUR OXYGEN BOTTLES WERE MISSING FORM THE RACK. A NUT UNSCREWED FROM A BOLT, CAUSING THE RETAINER BAR TO FAIL.  THIS BAR HOLDS THE BOTTLES IN PLACE.  THE DRIVER ALSO CHECKED AND RETIGHTENED THE BOLT AND NUT ON THE OTHER SIDE OF THE RACK.  THIS SIDE CONTAINED THE ACETYLENE BOTTLES.  HE SEARCHED FOR THE BOTTLES BETWEEN SCHRIEVER AND FRANKLIN, BUT DID NOT FIND THEM.  ON 8/2/95 THE LOUISIANA STATE POLICE REPORTED SOME BOTTLES NEAR HWY 20, EAST OF CHACAHOULA LA. THE LOCATION WAS SEARCHED AND THREE BOTTLES WERE LOCATED OFF THE HIGHWAY IN THE SWAM AND RECOVERED.  THERE WAS SOME GRASS MASHED DOWN CLOSER TO THE HIGHWAY, POSSIBLY INDICATING A BOTTLE WAS LAYING THERE.  POSSIBLY, IT WAS PICKED UP. IT IS STILL MISSING.  BOTTLE RACKS SHOULD BE CHECKED BY SHIPPERS AND DRIVERS TO INSURE THAT THE BOTTLES ARE SECURED.  A LOCK NUT THREADED ON THE BOLT OR A COTTER PIN THROUGH THE BOLT WOULD PREVENT THE RETAINER BAR FROM FAILING.

column168: A YARD SWITCH CREW REPORTED A FAINT ODOR COMING FROM THIS TANK CAR. ATSF EMERGENCY RESPONDERS ASSESSED CAR AND DETECTED A FAINT STENCH (THAT WAS CONSISTENT WITH THE PRODUCT) AND NOTED A PERCOLATING OR GURGLING SOUND. NO EVIDENCE OF RELEASED PRODUCT WAS FOUND ON THE CAR OR FITTINGS. THE CAR WAS ISOLATED FOR FURTHER OBSERVATION. THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED VIA CHEMTREC FOR ASSISTANCE. FROM A CONFERENCE CALL, THE SHIPPER OPTED TO SEND A RESPONSE TEAM, EVEN THOUGH THE CAR HAD NO FURTHER INDICATIONS OF A RELEASE AND THE PERCOLATION HAD CEASED. THE IMMANENT DANGER OF POLYMERIZATION WAS DISPELLED AS THERE WAS NO INDICATION OF EXCESSIVE TEMPERATURE (WHEN CHECKING THE TANK'S EXTERNAL SURFACE). THE SHIPPER'S RESPONSE TEAM EVALUATED THE CAR AT APPROXIMATELY 2000. THE PRODUCT CHECKED NEGATIVE FOR ANY CONTAMINATION OR POLYMERIZATION. A SLIGHT VACUUM WAS NOTED WHEN THE MANWAY WAS OPENED. A NITROGEN BLANKET HAD BEEN USED ON TOP OF THE PRODUCT.

column168: WHILE IN THE PROCESS OF UNLOADING TRAILER 8294 FROM PHILADELPHIA, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT A DRUM WAS LEAKING PRODUCT. AS A PRECAUTION WE ISOLATED THE TRAILER, PUT ABSORBENT MATERIAL IN AND UNDER TRAILER TO ABSORB ANY LIQUID AND CONTACTED A DISPOSAL COMPANY TO ASSESS THE SITUATION AND HANDLE CLEANUP. IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE XYLIDINE AS LEAKING FROM A SMALL CRACK IN THE WALL OF THE DRUM. ALL SAFETY PRECAUTIONS WERE TAKEN BY THE DISPOSAL COMPANY DURING CLEANUP. THE DAMAGED DRUM OF XYLIDINE WAS PLACED IN AN APPROVED RECOVERY DRUM AND HAS BEEN RETURNED TO DUPONT FOR THEIR INSPECTION. ALL HAZARDOUS RESIDUE WAS PROPERLY PACKAGED IN HAZARDOUS WASTE DRUMS OR BINS FOR DISPOSAL.

column168: WHILE DRIVER WAS DOING A WALK AROUND INSPECTION, NOTICED A DRIPPING FROM REAR DRAIN HOLE AT REAR OF TRAILER ALONG WITH BAD ODOR. ABLE TO STOP DRIPPING WITH LOCK GRIP PLYER. DRIVER CALLED PHONE NUMBER ON BILL OF LADING, WAS ADVISED TO CALL OKALAHOMA HWY PATROL. FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED AND WITH PROTECTIVE CLOTHING BROKE TRAILER SEAL AND OPENED TRAILER. TWO BOXES HAD TIPPED ONTO THEIR SIDE AND CAPS ON BOTTLES CAME LOOSE SATURATING TOP PORTION OF PACKAGING. FIRE DEPT REMOVED 12 BOXES, RINSED OUT TRAILER, TIGHTENED CAPS, RELOADED PRODUCT HOSED PARKING LOT, AND ALLOWED TRUCK PROCEED TO DESTINATION. KODAK ADVISED THAT CAPS WERE LOOSE, AND STATED THAT MACHINERY THAT DOES THAT JOB WOULD BE CHECKED.

HOSE HAD SMALL HOLE, LOAD UNDER PRESSURE. DRIVER RECEIVED TWO SMALL BURNS ON ARM.

A VAN TRAILER CONTAINING HAZARDOUS WASTE WAS ENROUTE FROM ELTEX CHEMICAL LOCATED AT 4050 HOMESTEAD ROAD IN HOUSTON, TX TO CLEAN HARBORS OF CLEVELAND, INC. LOCATED AT 2900 BROADWAY IN CLEVELAND. OH. DURING THE COURSE OF THE TRIP, THE DRIVER MADE A ROUTINE STOP AT CLEAN HARBORS LAKE CHARLES, LA IT WAS LOCATED AT 3184 CARBIDE DRIVE IN LAKE CHARLES, LA IT WAS DISCOVEREED THAT APPROXIMATELY 1 PINT OF MATERIAL HAD ESCAPED FROM THE TOP LID OF ONE OF THE CONTAINERS ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE VAN TRAILER WHERE IT WAS PREVENTED FROM ESCAPING TO THE ENVIRONMENT. INSPECTION OF THE CONTAINER INDICATED THAT A COMPLETE SEAL WAS NOT ACHIEVED WHEN THE TOP LID WAS SECURED. FACILITY PERSONNEL IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED THE RELEASE, ABSORBED ALL FREE LIQUIDS WITH SPEEDI DRY AND PLACED THE CONTAINER INTO A SUITABLE SALVAGE DRUM. ALL CLEAN-UP DEBRIS WAS PLACED IN THE SALVAGE DRUM AND WAS TRANSPORTED TO THE WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY INDICATED ON THE SHIPPING PAPER. PRIOR TO DEPARTURE FROM THE SHIPPER'SS LOCATION, THE LOAD WAS INSPECTED AND NO EVIDENCE OF LEAKING OR DAMAGE WAS OBSERVED. ALL DRIVERS AND LOADING PERSONNEL WILL CONTINUE TO INSPECT EACH CONTAINER AS IT IS LOADED AND TO TAKE APPROPRIATE ACTIONS IN THE EVENT A CONTAINER IS FOUND NOT TO BE STRUCTURALLY SOUND.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: THE BENETO TANKER TRUCK WAS HEADED SOUTH ON INTERSTATE 5 IN STANISLAUS COUNTY, CALIFORNIA WHEN IT APPROACHED THE CROWS LANDING EXIT.  THE TANKER TRUCK'S SPEED AT THIS TIME  WAS 55 MPH(PER TACHOMETER CHART) IN THE NUMBER 2 LANE WHEN OUR DRIVER NOTICED A VEHICLE PULLING AN AIRSTREAM TRAILER ATTEMPTING TO PASS HIM IN THE NUMBER 1 LANE.  THE TRAILER BEGAN TO SWAY FROM LEFT TO RIGHT EVENTUALLY FORCING OUR TANKER TRUCK TO MOVE TO THE RIGHT TO AVOID CONTACT.  AS THE TRAILER PASSED THE TANKER TRUCK IT STRUCK THE TANKERS STEERING AXLE FORCING IT OFF THE ROAD.  WHEN THE TANKER TIRES LOST CONTACT WITH THE PAVEMENT THE DRIVER LOST CONTROL AND THE TRUCK ROLLEDOVER.  IMMEDIATELY UPON LEARNING OF TH EACCIDENT, BENETO TANK LINES NOTIFIED ALL PROPER AUTHORITIES (BOTH FEDERAL AND STATE).  BY 12:OO AM ON JULY 7, 1995, THE SITE RESTORATION HAD BEEN COMPLETED TO THE SATISFACTION OF ALL STATE AND COUNTY AUTHORITIES.

ARRIVED AT UNLOADING SITE GAVE BILL TO RECEIVER FOR SIGNATURES PRIOR TO UNLOADING. THEN WAS TOLD WHERE TO HOOK UP AND TO UNLOAD, AND THAT THEY WERE EMPTY AND COULD HOLD IT ALL. THE DRIVER NOT REALIZING THE THERE WAS ONLY A 1500 GAL. TANK ON THE 3RD FLOOR EMPTIED OUT, WHICH OVERFLOWED TO THE ROOF AREA AND WAS CONTAINED AND NEUTRALIZED IN A HOLDING TANK.

DRIVER WAS LOADING ASPLITLOAD, (A LOAD OUT OF TWO TANKS.) A MISCALCULATION WAS MADE ON GAUGES, CAUSING TRUCK TANK TO FILL SOONER THAN CALCULATED. THE SPILL WAS DISCOVERED IMMEDIATELY AND WAS STOPPED. CALLS WERE MADE TO NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER, KANSAS DEPT. OF HEALTH & ENVIRONMENT, AND THE COUNTY ROAD DEPT. CLEANUP FOLLOWED. A SAFETY MEETING WAS HELD THE NEXT WEEK TO REVIEW THE INCIDENT AND ACTIONS WERE DISCUSSED TO PREVENT THIS IN THE FUTURE.

column168: WHILE INSPECTION CARGO AT TRUCKSTOP, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT ONE (1) DRUM WAS LEAKING DO TO A LOOSE LID. DRIVER HAD TRIED TO TIGHTEN LID TO NO AVAIL. LID WAS REMOVED AND SILICONE PLACED AROUND GASKET AND LID WAS RESEALED. NO FURTHER LEAKAGE OCCURED. LOAD PROCEEDED ON TO DESTINATION WITH NO FURTHER PROBLEM. NO MATERIAL LEAKED OUTSIDE TRAILER.

UPON DEPARTURE OF THE SAVANNA ARMY DEPOT WITH A SHIPMENT OF 1.1E ROCKETS, THE TSMT TRUCK HAD TRAVELLED 8 MILES ON IL STATE 84 WHEN THE DRIVER NOTICED THE RIGHT REAR TRAILER SMOKING. INSPECTION REVEALED THE RIGHT REAR BRAKE WAS ON FIRE. THE DRIVER PUSHED THE "PANIC BUTTON" ON HIS QUALCOMM SATALLITE SYSTEM WHICH BROUGHT AN IMMEDIATE RESPONSE FROM THE LOCAL FIRE DEPT., AND POLICE DEPARTMENT. THE FIRE WAS EXTINGUISHED BY THE DRIVERS WITH THEE AID OF SOME PASSING MOTORIST. DUE TO THE NATURE OF THE CARGO, IT WAS DECIDED TO EVACUATE ONE MILE RADIUS AROUND THE TRUCK AND CLOSE SR84 TO ALL TRAFFIC. THIS PLAN WAS DISCARDED WHEN IT WAS DISCOVERED THE PROBLEM WAS AN OVERHEATED BRAKE. THE TRUCK WAS ESCORTED BACK TO SAVANNA ARMY DEPOT. FURTHE INVESTIGATION REVEALED THE SLACK ADJUSTER WAS SLIGHTLY BENT THUS PREVENTING THE BRAKE FROM RELEASING COMPLETELY. REPORT WAS MADE TO THE NATIONAL RESPONSE.

column168: OUR TRUCK ENROUTE TO TOLLESON AZ TO FULLERTON CA WITH FULL LOAD OF JUNK BATTERIES COLLIDED WITH ANOTHER TRUCK, LEFT THE ROADWAY AND OVERTURNED INTO THE CANAL OF THE SALT RIVER PROJECT IN MARICOPA COUNTY BUT OUTSIDE THE CITY LIMITS OF PHOENIX AZ. THIS ACCIDENT ATTRIBUTED ENTIRELY TO NEGLIGENT OPERATION BY DRIVER (THERE REMAINS AT TIME OF THIS REPORT A QUESTION OF DRIVER IMPAIRMENT). THE HAZ MAT PEOPLE OF ARIZONA DPS AND ENVIRONMENTAL ENGINEERS FOR SALT RIVER PROJECT AT THE SCENE AND WERE DIRECTLY INVOLVED WITH THE CLEANUP AND REMOVAL. ACTION IN REGARD TO DRIVER PENDING LAB REPORTS STILL UNAVAILABLE AT THIS DATE.

UTLX WAS FOUND LEAKING IN YARD AT CURTIS BAY, MARYLAND. THE LEAK WAS A SLOW TRICKLE. THE CONSIGNEE IS LOCATED ADJACENT TO YARD AND RESPONDED TO SECURE AT TRAIN MASTERS REQUEST. THE CONSIGNEE'S (VISTA CHEMICAL) HAZMAT MADE REPAIRS TO THE CAR TO STOP THE LEAK. THE LEAK WAS PLUGGED AND THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS ABSORBED AND NEUTRALIZED. THE CAR WAS MOVED TO VISTA CHEMICAL FOR ADDITIONAL REPAIRS.

I HAD FILLED (2) 275 GALLON TANKS. WHEN I TURNED THE NOZZLE OFF, THE HOSE CONNECTION AT THE NOZZLE CRACKED AND SPRAYED FUEL. SPILL CREW WAS CALLED FOR CLEANUP. THIS HOSE/NOZZLE WAS REPLACED AFTER THIS INCIDENT.

ON 7-11-95 RAMP SUPERVISOR BRUCE GARMEN REPORTED A UNIT LOAD DEVICE EMITTING AN ODOR ON THE MAIN CARGO DECK OF THE AIRCRAFT. I, MICHAEL FRYE, HAZ MAT COORDINATOR AND RANDY WILLIAMS, HAZ MAT TECHNICIAN, REPONDED. UPON ARRIVAL ON THE SCENE I PLACED THE GAS DETECTION INSTRUMENT INSIDE THE AIRCRAFT. NO ABNORMAL READINGS WERE OBSERVED. I DID DETECT A STRONG ODOR. TECHNICIANS WILLIAMS AND CORDREY DONNED STRUCTURAL FIREFIGHTING GEAR AND SELF-CONTAINED BREATHING APPARATUS TO REMOVE THE UNIT LOAD DEVICE FROM THE MAIN CARGO DECK.  INSIDE THE LOAD UNIT DEVICE THEY FOUND A FIBERBOARD BOX THAT WAS LEAKING. UPON INVESTIGATION, THEY FOUND A SMALLER FIBERBOARD BOX WITHIN. INSIDE THAT WERE 12 GLASS RECEPTACLES WITH SCREW-TYPE CLOSURES, EACH WITH 8 OZ CAPACITY. THERE WAS NO POSITIVE MEANS TO SECURE THESE CLOSURES. TWO OF THE GLASS RECEPTACLES LEAKED THEIR ENTIRE CONTENTS. THE INNER FIBERBOARD WAS NOT PROPERLY BLOCKED AND BRACED INSIDE THE OUTER FIBERBOARD BOX. THERE WAS A SHIPPING INVOICE THAT STATED THE MATERIAL TO BE: "PHOSPHORIC ACID." THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELS, OR PROPER CERTIFICATION ACCOMPANYING THIS SHIPMENT TO INDICATE THAT ITS CONTENTS WERE REGULATED AS HAZ MAT. THIS SHIPMENT IS AT THE HAZ MAT SORT, IN THE SECURITY CAGE, UNDER LOCK AND KEY PENDING INVESTIGATION BY THE FAA.

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 9:00 A.M. ON JULY 14, 1995 I RECEIVED A PHONE CALL FROM N&M TRANSFER DRIVER RICK GORGES. MR GORGES ADVISED ME BY TELEPHONE THAT HE HAD JUST PULLED IN TO HIS FIRST STOP, WHICH WAS THE DOCK AT HYDRITE CHEMICAL, LACROSSE, WISCONSIN. AFTER OPENING THE TRAILER DOOR, HE IMMEDIATELY NOTICED THAT A SMALL AMOUNT OF LEAKAGE HAD TAKEN PLACE ON THE FLOOR OF THE BACK QUARTER OF HIS TRAILER. MR GORGES IDENTIFIED THE LEAKING CONTAINERS AS 6 OR 7 (15) GALLON POLYETHYLENE DRUMS THAT HAD FALLEN ON THEIR SIDE WHILE IN TRANSIT. EACH ONE OF THE DRUMS HAD LEAKAGE FROM THE VENTING CAPS ON THE TOP OF THE DRUMS. COMPANY EMPLOYEES AT HYDRITE CHEMICAL IN LACROSSE REMOVED THE ENTIRE SHIPMENT, (CONSISTING OF 15 AND 55 GALLON DRUMS-SEE PHOTOS) AND THEN APPLIED NEUTRALIZER TO THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER. THE ATTACHED PHOTOGRAPHS INDICATE THE DEGREE TO WHICH THE FLOOR WAS SATURATED. IMPROPER BLOCKING AND POOR SECUREMENT WAS THE MAJOR CAUSE OF THIS SPILL. N&M TRANSFER DOCK EMPLOYEES HAVE BEEN NOTIFIED ABOUT PROPER BLOCKING TECHNIQUES FOR ALL DIFFERENT SIZE DRUMS OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. THE INDIVIDUAL DOCK EMPLOYEE RESPONSIBLE FOR THE LOADING OF THIS TRAILER WILL RECEIVE A NOTICE OF DISCIPLINARY ACTION.

column168: DEAN C COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED BY MARTY VASQUEZ, MANAGER, YARD OPERATIONS, LOS ANGELES, THAT THERE WAS A TANK CAR IN THE YARD THAT WAS BEING HANDLED DURING NORMAL SWITCHING OPERATIONS AND NOTED BY THE SWITCH CREW TO BE LEAKING FROM THE TOP PORTION OF THE CAR EVERY TIME IT WAS MOVED. THE CAR WAS SET TO YARD TRACK #213 AND ISOLATED PENDING INSPECTION. MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE YARD FACILITY, INSPECTED THE CAR AND FOUND THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK TO BE FROM THE BREATHER VENT LOCATED ON THE "B" END OF THE CAR, OUTSIDE OF THE CENTER PLATFORM AREA. THE TOP RETAINER PLATE TO THE BREATHER VENT HAS AN EIGHT BOLT PATTERN, 3/8" X 1" BOLTS WERE LAYING ON TOP OFTHE PLATE, AND MOVE WAS COMPLETELY MISSING. THE REMAINING FIVE BOLTS WERE REMOVED BY HAND, AS THE EXISTING BOLT THREADS HAD NOTHING TO TIGHTEN TO. WHILE THERE WAS ADEQUATE THREAD LEFT ON THE BOLTS THEMSELVES, THE BOLT HOLES IN THE HOUSING, WHICH WOULD NORMALLY HAVE AN IDENTICAL THREAD PATTERN HAD NO ABILITY TO RETAIN THE ONE INCH BOLTS. UPON REMOVING ALL OF THE BOLTS AND THE RETAINER COVER, OBSERVED THE BOTTOM CERAMIC FILTER GASKET TO BE PULLED HALF WAY FROM UNDERNEATH THE FILTER AND FOLDED OVER THE TOP FILTER. THE SPACER WAS REMOVED AND THE BOTTOM GASKET, ALONG WITH THE BOTTOM SCREEN WHICH WAS ALSO ASKEW, WAS PROPERLY POSITIONED. THE FILTER AND TOP GASKET, ALONG WITH THE RETAINER, WERE THEN REPLACED AND THE RETAINER PLATE SET INTO PLACE. AS A MAJORITY OF THE EXISTING BOLTS WOULD NOT TIGHTEN TO THE HOUSING, REPLACEMENT BOLTS WERE INSTALLED. ONLY TWO OF THE EXISTING BOLTS WOULD THREAD DOWN AND TIGHTEN. FOUR 3/8" X 1 1/2" BOLTS WERE OBTAINED AND INSTALLED TO FURTHER SECURE THE RETAINER PLATE. TWO OF THE BOLT HOLES WERE STRIPPED OUT AND WOULD NOT ACCEPT EVEN THE 1 1/2" BOLTS. THE SIX BOLTS TEMPORARILY SECURED THE THAINER SO THE CAR COULD BE MOVED TO THE CONSIGNEE FOR OFF LOADING OF THE PRODUCT. NOTIFICATIONS WERE ONLY MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSES AND TO THE SHIPPER FOR CORRECTIVE ACTION.

column168: DEAN C COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY DANA FONTAINE, TERMINAL MANAGER, LOS ANGELES CHEMICAL, SOUTH GATE, CALIFORNIA, REPORTING A TANK CAR THAT HAD BEEN DELIVERED TO HIS FACILITY, WHICH WAS COVERED WITH PRODUCT. MR. FONTAINE WAS REQUESTING AN INSPECTION OF THE CAR, AND A REPLACEMENT FRANGIBLE DISC INORDER TO OFF LOAD THE PRODUCT. MANAGER COOPER WAS ALSO CONTACTED BY THE SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVE, PHILIP LUZMOOR, SOLVAY, WHO WAS CONCERNED OVER THE OUTWARD APPEARANCE OF THE PRODUCT COVERING THE TOP PORTION OF THE CAR. MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE LOS ANGELES CHEMICAL FACILITY AND MET WITH MR. FONTAINE. THE TANK CAR WAS PLACED ON ONE OF THEIR TRACKS WHERE THEY OFF LOAD THE PRODUCT. THE CAR HAD BEEN CLEANED PRIOR TO MANAGER COOPER'S ARRIVAL DUE TO NEW CUSTOMERS TOURING THE FACILITY AND THE APPEARANCE OF GOOD HOUSEKEEPING. MR. FONTAINE PROVIDED TWO POLAROID PHOTOS WHICH SHOWED THE CAR COVERED ACROSS THE TOP CENTER PORTION WITH PRODUCT. INSPECTION OF THE CAR DEVELOPED THE PROBABLE SOURCE OF THE RELEASE TO BE FROM THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE. THIS CAR DID NOT HAVE A SAFETY VENT WITH A FRANGIBLE DISC. IT APPEARS THE CAR WAS ROUGH HANDLED EITHER IN TRAIN PLACEMENT OR SWITCHING OPERATIONS. THE CAR SUSTAINED A ROUGH IMPACT WHICH CAUSED THE PRODUCT TO SURGE WITH ENOUGH FORCE TO ACTIVATE THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE. ONCE OPEN, THE PRODUCT SPRAYED UP THROUGH THE VALVE AND ACROSS THE CENTER WORK PLATFORM AREA OF THE CAR. THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE IS A MIDLAND STYLE VALVE, LOCATED OUTSIDE THE CENTER PLATFORM ON THE "B" END OF THE CAR. THE REMAINING VALVES AND FITTINGS WERE INSPECTED AND FOUND TO BE SECURE. AS THE CAR HAD ALL READY BEEN CLEANED, THE ONLY REMAINING ACTIVITY WAS TO OFF LOAD THE PRODUCT. UPON THE CAR BEING RETURNED TO SOLVAY, IT WAS SUGGESTED THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE BE BENCH TESTED TO VARIFY THAT IT WAS OPERATIONAL AT IT'S REQUIRED TEST PRESSURE. DUE TO THE NATURE OF THE DISCOVERY, AND THE TYPE AND AMOUNT OF PRODUCT RELEASED, NOTIFICATION WAS ONLY MADE TO THE SHIPPER.

THERE WERE 4 DRUMS ON A WOODEN SKID WRAPPED WITH A SMALL AMOUNT OF SHRINKWRAP AND NOT BRACEDON BOTH SIDES. THE SPILL WAS REPORTED TO THE ORIGIN SERVICE CENTER DIRECTOR FOR TRAINING OF THE LOADING ASSOCIATES. INSTRUCTIONS WILL BE GIVEN ON USING THE PROPER AMOUNT OF SHRINKWRAP AND BRACING TO SECURE DRUMS.

column168: OUR DRIVER WAS MAKING A BULK DELIVERY OF GASOLINE TO THE UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANKS AT A CONVENIENCE STORE.  THERE ARE TWO REGULAR UNLEADED GASOLINE TANKS AT THIS STORE THAT ARE MANIFOLDED TOGETHER.  OUR DRIVER HAD FILLED ON OF THE TWO TANKS AND HAD STARTED TO FILL THE 2ND ONE WHEN PRESSURE IN THE TANK FORCED THE CAP OFF OF THE 1ST TANK.  THIS CAUSED ABOUT 10 GALLONS OF GAS TO SPILL ONTO THE CONCRETE AROUND THE FILL PIPES. INVESTIGATION REVEALED THAT THE CHECK VALVE ON THE VENT LINE FOR THE 2ND TANK HAD STUCK CLOSED CAUSING PRESSURE TO BUILD IN THE TANK.  THE NEW YORK STATE DEPT. OF ENVIRONMENTAL CONSERVATION WAS NOTIFIED AND THEIR REFERENCE NUMBER FOR THIS INCIDENT IS 94-04949.

column168: REGIONAL MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY DEAN L WHITELEY, PORTLAND, OR, WAS NOTIFIED BY UNION PACIFIC MOTOR FREIGHT ALBINA YARD TERMINAL MANAGER BILL CARTER, PORTLAND, OR. THAT YELLOW FREIGHT TRAILER YFSZ 115870 BILLED TO CONTAIN 20 DRUMS, 14440 POUNDS, SULPHUR CHLORIDES, AND FREIGHT ALL KINDS, WAS LEAKING. INSPECTION DEVELOPED SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT ON DECK OF FLATCAR, DAMPNESS ALONG WITH COAGULATED PRODUCT UNDERNEATH TRAILER. TRAILER WAS GROUNDED/ISOLATED AND DUE TO PUNGENT ODOR AND POTENTIAL REACTION WITH MOISTURE. IMMEDIATE ACTION WAS TAKEN TO SECURE MSDS BY CONTACTING YELLOW FREIGHT, PORTLAND, OR., FOR SHIPPER/CONSIGNEE INFORMATION. CONSIGNEE JAMES RIVER CORP, CAMAS, WA., SUPPLIED MSDS AND VOLUNTERED EMERGENCY RESPONSE ASSISTANCE ACCOUNT KNOWLEDGE OF PRODUCT AND RECENT TRAINING ON SPECIFIC PRODUCT. YELLOW FREIGHT CORPORATION, KANSAS CITY, MO., REQUESTED OLYMPUS ENVIRONMENTAL, PORTLAND, OR., TO RESPOND. THE SINGLE VERTICAL OPENING DOOR WAS PROTECTED WITH INTACT SEAL YFS9590168. SOME DIFFICULTY WAS EXPERIENCED OPENING DOOR ACCOUNT CARDBOARD CARTONS AGAINST DOOR. UPON OPENING NOTICED CARDBOARD CARTONS STACKED TO WITHIN 3 FEET OF ROOF COMPLETELY ACROSS OPENING. SUFFICIENT CARTONS, ALL SHOWING EVIDENCE OF PRODUCT CONTAMINATION AND DETERIORATION, WERE REMOVED TO LOCATE THE 20 DRUMS MOVING SINGLE LAYER IN NOSE OF TRAILER. JAMES RIVER FORCES ENETERED TRAILER AND FOUND THREE DRUMS WITH LOOSE 2 INCH SCREW BUNGS AND SPILLED PRODUCT ON TOP. THE BUNGS WERE SECURED AND SODIUM BICARBONATE WAS SPREAD ON TOP AND AROUND DRUMS TO NEUTRALIZE/STABILIZE SHIPMENT. CARTON REMOVAL CONTINUED UNTIL DARKNESS WHEN TRAILER WAS SECURED PENDING FURTHER CLEANUP. ON JULY 11, 1995, OLYMPUS ENVIRONMENTAL CONTINUED CLEANUP. THE 20 DRUMS WERE FOUND IN UPRIGHT CONDITION WITH NO EVIDENCE OF ROUGH HANDLING. THERE WAS NO BLOCKING OR BRACING INSTALLED IN TRAILER. ONE WOODEN PALLET WAS FOUND IN A VOID IN NOSE OF TRAILER AND A 4X8 SHEET OF PLYWOOD SEPARATED DRUMS FROM FAK SHIPMENT. WHEN THE DRUMS WERE REMOVED, ALL WERE NOTED WITH PRODUCT STAINING AROUND BOTTOM CHIME. SOME DRUMS DISPLAYED RUBBING ACTION IN AREA OF ROLLING HOOPS. ONE DRUM WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING APPROXIMATELY 1 PINT PER HOUR FROM THE BOTTOM CHIME AREA. ALL DRUMS WERE OVERPACKED ACCOUNT POTENTIAL FOR FURTHER LEAKAGE. THE INSIDE NOSE AND ROOF AREA OF TRAILER WAS CONTAMINATED WITH PRODUCT. THIS RESULTED FROM INTERNAL PRESSURE BUILD-UP DURING TRANSPORTATION DUE TO AGITATION, TEMPERATURE CHANGE, AND ELEVATION CHANGES. THE LOOSE BUNGS ALLOWED THE MATERIAL TO ESCAPE AND SPRAY THROUGHOUT INTERIOR OF TRAILER. THE FAK PORTION OF SHIPMENT WILL BE DISPOSED OF AS HAZARDOUS WASTE. DISPOSITION OF DRUMS/PRODUCT IS PENDING. DECONTAMINATION OF TRAILER IS CONTINUING AND DISPOSITION IS UNKNOWN. THE FOLLOWING INDIVIDUALS WERE FURNISHED DETAILS. BOB ZABO AND SHAWN DYER, FERRO CORP, WALTON HILLS, OH. A/C216-641-8585. TED MORRIS,JAMES RIVER CORP, CAMAS, WA., A/C360-834-8465. KEN, YELLOW FREIGHT, A/C503-735-2282. BOB ORR, OLYMPUS ENVIRO

column168: ON 072695 AT APPROXIMATELY 330AM REEDER RECEIVED A CALL FROM CORRIDOR MGR RON BAIN THAT THE ABOVE CAR WAS LEAKING AT DEQUINCY, LA. ALL TRAIN TRAFFIC HAD BEEN STOPPED BY BAIN FOR SAFETY. REEDER ADVISED THAT UNLESS THERE WAS A VISIBLE VAPOR CLOUD ACROSS THE MAIN LINE, TRAINS COULD PASS AT MAIN LINE SPEEDS IF THE CREW CLOSED THEIR WINDOWS AND DOORS AND SHUT OFF FRESH AIR INTAKES. UPON ARRIVAL AT THE SCENE, REEDER OBSERVED A SMALL VAPOR CLOUD COMING FROM THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING. REEDER REMOVED SEAL TRIAD CHEMICAL 043400. UPON OPENING THE COVER, LIQUID AMMONIA COULD BE SEEN BUBBLING ON THE MANWAY PLATE. THE APPARENT SOURCE OF THE LEAK WAS THE PACKING STEM ON THE LIQUID VALVE AT THE B END OF THE CAR. REEDER TIGHTENED THE RETAINING THE RETAINING NUT AND STOPPED THE LEAK. A LARGE PIECE OF TEFLON TAPE WAS DISCOVERED WRAPPED AROUND THE VALVE STEM. THIS SEEMS TO INDICATE THE VALVE HAD BEEN LEAKING PREVIOUSLY AND SOMEONE HAD ATTEMPTED TO REPAIR IT. THE CAR WAS RESEALED WITH UNION PACIFIC Y 725129. CHEMTREC AND THE SHIPPER WERE NOTIFIED. THIS CAR WAS RELEASED FOR NORMAL MOVEMENT WITHOUT DELAY.

ZERWECK INSPECTED AND FOUND DRIPS AT THE RATE OF 1 QUART PER HOUR COMING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET. THE TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET WAS TIGHTENED AS WAS THE 2" PLUG AND PLUG NIPPLE. THE LEAK WOULD NOT STOP AND IT WAS DETERMINED THE VALVE WAS BAD AFTER REPEATING ATTEMPTS TO RESEAT THE VALVE BY OPENING AND CLOSING IT. REGIONAL MANAGER TOM ROBINSON WAS CONTACTED AND RESPONDED. CHEMTREC, TOM FLORES, WAS NOTIFIED AND HAD THE SHIPPER FINA CALL ZERWECK. FINA ARRANGED FOR LUCKY LADY TRANSPORT TO OFF LOAD THE PRODUCT AND RETURN IT TO THE BIG SPRING PLANT. ROBINSON AND ZERWECK, ASSISTED BY THE TRANSPORT DRIVERS COMPLETED TRANLOADING OF THE PRODUCT AT 1630 HRS ON 073195, WITHOUT INCIDENT.

WHILE CONDUCTING REGULATORY COMPLIANCE INSPECTIONS AT ELKO NV MGR HW RODABOUGH INSPECTED TANKCAR KCCX2711, LOADED CAR OF SULFURIC ACID. NOTED FRANGIBLE DISC HAD FAILED. MGR RODABAUGH INSTALLED BS&B 100 LB DISC IN BAFFLED SAFETY VANT MOUNTED INSIDE THE WORKING PLATFORM. CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED. MR JOE BILAZZO WAS FURNISHED WITH DETAILS AND CASE #37640 WAS ASSIGNED. MR WAYNE STOCKERBRAND KENNECOT, UT. COPPER WAS ALSO NOTIFIED REGARDING DETAILS.

WHILE CONDUCTING REGULATORY COMPLIANCE INSPECTIONS AT ELKO NV MGR HW RODABOUGH INSPECTED TANKCAR NATX81005, LOADED CAR OF FUEL OIL. NOTED CAR LEAKING FROM THE TOP, INSPECTION REVEALED FUEL LEAKING FROM 2" BALL VALVE ON THE EDUCTION PIPE, LEAK FOUND AT THE OPERATING ROD. BECAUSE OF THE HIGH AMBIENT TEMPERATURE THE CAR HAD SELF-PRESSURIZED FORCING THE PRODUCT UP THE EDUCTION PIPE, CREATING THE LEAKING CONDITION. THE VALVE WAS DISASSEMBLED BY MGR RODABOUGH, THERE WAS NO PACKING ON THE OPERATING ROD, MGR RODABOUGH APPLIED TEMPORARY TEFLON PACKING, WHICH STOPPED THE LEAK. CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED, MR JOE MILAZZO FURNISHED WITH DETAILS AND CASE #37641 WAS ASSIGNED. KOCH REFINING WAS ALSO INFORMED REGARDING DETAILS OF THE INCIDENT.

ONE OF OUR DRIVERS, JACK FUNK, WAS ENROUTE TO MINERVA, OHIO TO MAKE ONE OF MANY DELIVERY STOPS SCHEDULED FOR THE DAY. WHILE PASSING THROUGH ROBERTSVILLE, OHIO ON RT 30, APPROXIMATELY THREE MILES WEST OF MINERVA, A DOG SUDDENLY RAN OUT INTO THE STREET IN FRONT OF HIS UNIT. JACK APPLIED HIS BRAKES SLOWING HIS UNIT TO 20 MPH FROM THE 30 MPH HE HAD BEEN DRIVING. HE CONTINUED DRIVING TO HIS FIRST STOP IN MINERVA AND WHEN HE BEGAN OFFLOADING THE DELIVERY, HE DISCOVERED THAT ONE OF THE SIX 55 GALLONS DRUMS SCHEDULED FOR DELIVERY TO RED HEAD BRAS COMPANY IN SHREVE, OHIO HAD TURNED OVER ON IT'S SIDE SPILLING A SMALL QUANTITY OF PRODUCT ONTO THE BED OF THE TRAILER. PART OF THE PRODUCT LEAKED THROUGH THE TRAILER AND OUT ONTO THE ASPHALT PARKING LOT. A MEMBER OF OUR EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM WAS SENT TO THE INCIDENT SITE TO ASSIST IN THE NEUTRALIZATION AND CLEANUP OF THE SPILL AND IT WAS RETURNED TO THE BRANCH IN A SALVAGE DRUM. DUE TO IT'S DENSITY, ONLY THREE DRUMS OF SULFURIC ACID ARE LOADED ONTO EACH PALLET VERSUS FOUR DRUMS FOR LIGHTER PRODUCTS. ALTHOUGH ALL DRUMS ARE BANDED TOGETHER ON EACH PALLET WITH STRAPPING, THERE IS STILL THE POTENTIAL FOR SOME SHIFTING IN THE EVENT THE UNIT IS FORCED TO BRAKE SUDDENLY AS WAS THE CASE HERE. WE FEEL THE FORCE OF 750 POUNDS OF PRODUCT IN THE DRUM SUDDENLY PUSHING AGAINST THE BUNG WHEN IT FELL OVER MAY HAVE BEEN ENOUGH TO FORCE IT'S WAY PAST THE BUNG. WE WILL INVESTIGATE ALTERNATE METHODS OF SECURING THE PALLETS WITH THREE DRUMS ON THEM IN THE TRAILER.

WHILE PROCEEDING EASTBOUND ON I-40, 8 MILES WEST OF ALBUQUERQUE, NM, TSMT DRIVER HEARD A LOUD NOISE IN THE TRAILER. DRIVER PULLED OFF AT EXIT 149 AND UPON INVESTIGATION DISCOVERED ONE (1) DRUM ON LAST ROW NEAR REAR OF TRAILER THAT APPEARED TO BE ON FIRE. THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY PUSHED THE PANIC BUTTON THE QUALCOMM SATILLITE TRACKING SYSTEM AT 23:54 CDT. THE ALBUQUERQUE FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS CONTACTED AS WEL AS THE NEW MEXICO STATE PATROL. BOTH AGENCIES RESPONDED AND THE FIRE WAS EXTINGUISHED. THE FIRE WAS CONFINED TO THE ONE DRUM. CONTACT WAS MADE WITH THE SHIPPER, CHEMICAL WASTE MANAGEMENT, AZUSA, CA. ACCORDING TO CWM PERSONNEL, THIS HAD ORIGINATED AT PEARL HARBOR, HI AND WAS GENERATED FRO A LARGE REMEDATION PROJECT. THIS PRODUCT WAS TO CONTAIN SLUDGE FROM THE PETROLEUM REFINING INDUSTRY. CHEMICAL WASTE MANAGEMENT SEPCULATE THAT SOME ORGANIC MATERIAL MAY HAVE CONTAMINATED THIS PRODUCT WHICH CAUSED IT TO SPONTANEOUSLY COMBUST. ONCE THE FIRE WAS EXSTINGUISHED, A COMPANY CALLED RINCHEM WAS CONTRACTEDTO OVERPACK THE DRUM AND PREPARE THE SHIPMENT TO GO ON TO DESTINATION. NO MATERIAL WAS SPILLED OR LEAKED INTO THE ENVIRONMENT. THE REST OF THE TRIP WAS COMPLETED WITH FREQUENT INSPECTIONS MADE BY THE DRIVER. NO FURTHER PROBLEMS WERE ENCOUNTERED. IT SHOUDL BE NOTED THAT SEVERAL ATTEMPTS WERE MADE TO NOTIFY THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER BEGINNING AT 00:10, 7-21-95 WITH CONTACT FINNALY MADE 00:50, REPORT NO. 300780. THE NEW MEXICO ENVIRONMENT DEPARTMENT WAS NOTIFIED AT 00:48.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: MCGIL SPECIAL SERVICES TRUCK WAS PROCEEDING EASTBOUND ON I-40 NEAR FORREST CITY, AR. THE DRIVER MADE A LANE CHANGE FROM THE RIGHT LANE TO THE LEFT LANE. WHILE MAKING THIS LANE CHANGE, THE DRIVER STATE HE REACHED DOWN TO GET HIS CUP OF COFFEE AND IN THE PROCESS HE ALLOWED THE TRUCK TO MOVE TO FAR TO THE LEFT AND INTO THE MEDIAN AT WHICH TIME HE COULD NOT REGAIN CONTROL. THE TRUCK TURNED OVER ON ITS LEFT SIDE. THE CARGO CARRYING PORTION WAS 20 FOOT SEA CONTAINER ON A 48 FOOT FLATBED SECURED WITH SIX(6) 5/16" GRADE 70 CHAINS. THE CHAINS BROKE ALLOWING THE CONTAINER TO ROLL FREE FROM THE TRAILER. THE DOORS OF THE CONTAINER WERE SPRUNG OPEN ALLOWING SEVERAL FIBERBOARD BOXES OF PRODUCT OUT ONTO THE GROUND. THERE WAS NO EVACUATION HOWEVER I-40 WAS CLOSED FOR APPROXIMATELY 1 HOUR. THE ARKANSAS STATE POLICE RESPNDED AS WELL AS THE FORREST CITY FIRE DEPARTMENT. THE DRIVER RECEIVED SCRAPES AND LACERATIONS OT HIS LEFT SIDE AND THE CO-DRIVER, WHO WAS IN THE SLEEPER BERTH RECEIVED SOME BROKEN RIBS. NONE OF THE INJURIES WERE LIFE THREATENING. THE EQUIPMENT WAS REMOVED FROM THE SCENE AND THE PRODUCT TRANSLOADED TO ANOTHER TRUCK. THE PRODUCT PROCEEDED ON TO THE DESTINATION. THE NATIONAL RESPONSE WAS NOTIFIEDAT 03:20 CDT, REPORT NO. 300128.

TH C LIQUID NITROGEN TO ENTER THE CARGO TANK FRONT HEAD AT THE HEAD WELD ALLOWED LIQ VENTED FROM THE VEHICLE VENT SYSTEM TO EMPTY THE CONTENTS OF THE CARGO TANK. ON 7/22/95 RAMP SUPERVISOR BARRY BACH REPORTED A SHIPMENT EMITTING AN ODOR IN THE BELLY OF AIRCRAFT AT GATE B-43. I, MICHAEL A FRYE, HAZ MAT COORDINATOR, AND HAZ MAT TECHNICIAN, THEO GHOSTSTONE, RESPONDED. UPON ARRIVAL, I TOOK THE GAS DETECTION INSTRUMENT IN THE BELLY. NO ABNORMAL READINGS WERE OBSERVED BUT I DID DETECT AN ODOR OF "RUBBING ALCOHOL." INSIDE THE BELLY WAS A FIBERBOARD BOX THAT WAS LOADED ON ITS SIDE. THE TOP OF THE FIBERBOARD BOX WAS WET. UPON INVESTIGATION OF THE INNER CONTENTS, I FOUND FOUR 1 GALLON CAPACITY PLASTIC RECEPTACLES WITH SCREW-TYPE CLOSURES. THERE WAS NO POSITIVE MEANS TO SECURE THE CLOSURES. THIS SHIPMENT WAS PROPERLY MARKED, LABELED AND PROPER CERTIFICATION DID ACCOMPANY THIS SHIPMENT. THIS SHIPMENT WAS PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM ANF FORWARDED ONTO ITS DESTINATION.

ON JULY 27, 1995, AT 03:14 HAZ MAT SORT RHONDA CLONCH REPORTED A SPILL WITH AN ODOR. THE SPILL WAS LOCATED OUTSIDE OF THE HAZ MAT AREA IN A CARGO CONTAINER. HAZ MAT COORDINATOR ADDIE CAMPTON AND SPILL TECHNICIAN THEO GHOSTONE RESPONDED. UPON OUR INVESTIGATION, WE DISCOVERED A WET FIBREBOARD BOX. UPON INSEPCTION OF THE INNER CONTENTS, WE DISCOVERED A SMALL METAL RECEPTACLE WITH A SCREW-TYPE CLOSURE. THIS RECEPTACLE CONTIANED APPROXIMATELY 1 GAL OF A REGULATED MATERIAL AS FOLLOWS. "#2 FUEL OIL", "FLAMMABLE LIQUID", "UN1203". THIS SHIPMENT WAS CLEARLY MARKED AND LABELED AS HAZ MAT AND CERTIFICATION DID ACCOMPANY THIS SHIPMENT. HOWEVER, AFTER REPACKING THIS SHIPMENT IN A SALVAGE DRUM WITH ABSORBENT, PREPARING TO FORWARD IT ON, WE DISCOVERED THE CERTIFICATION WAS INCORRECT. THIS SHIPMENT WILL BE HELD UNTIL PROPER CERTIFICATION IS RECEIVED. THE ONLY THEORY WE HAVE FOR THSI SHIPMENT LEAKING IS DAMAGE OF THE INNER METAL RECEPTACLE AND THE CLOSURE. CLEAR OF SCENE 04:13.

ON JULY 25, 1995, AT 03:43, HAZ MAT AREA MANAGER JIM CURTIS REPORTED A SPILL WITH AN ODOR. THE SPILL WAS LOCATED OUTSIDE THE HAZ MAT AREA IN A CARGO CONTAINER. HAZ MAT COORDINATOR ADDIE CAMPTON AND SPILL TECHNICIAN THEO GHOSTONE RESPONDED. UPON OUR INVESTIGATION, WE DISCOVERED A FIBERBOARD BOX SATURATED AND CLEARLY MARKED AS HAZ MAT. UPON FURTHER INSPECTION OF THE BOX AND INNER CONTENTS, WE FOUND IT TO CONTAIN APPROXIMATELY 9 GLASS RECEPTACLES WITH SCREW-TYPE CLOSURES AND EACH BOTTLE WRAPPED SEPARATELY IN BUBBLE WRAP. WE DISCOVERED ONE GLASS RECEPTACLE WITH THTE CLOSURE LOOSE AND ALL CONTENTS LOST. ALL OF THE GLASS RECEPTACLES CONTAINED DIFFERENT FLAVORINGS. THE FLAVOR OF THE RECPTACLE THAT LEAKED WAS CINNAMON. THIS WAS A REGULATED MATERIAL THAT WAS CLEARLY MARKED AND LABELED AS THE FOLLOWING: "EXTRACTS, FLAVORING LIQUID 3, UN1197, LIMITED QUANTITY." CORRECT CERTIFICATION DID ACCOMPANY THE SHIPMENT. THIS SHIPMENT WAS PLACED IN PLASTIC BAGS WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL AND PLACED IN A SALVAGE DRUM AND FORWARDED ON TO THE CONSIGNEE. THE ONLY THEORY WE HAVE FOR THIS SHIPMENT LEAKING IS A FAULTY CLOSURE. CLEAR OF SCENE AT 04:57.

THERE WERE NO OTHER MARKINGS ON THE BOXES TO INDICATE THAT SOME OF THESE CONTAINED REGULATED ITEMS AND THERE WERE NO DANGEROUS GOODS SHIPPERS DECLARATIONS ACCOMPANYING THE SHIPMENT. THE ONLY THEORY WE HAVE FOR THIS SHIPMENT LEAKING IS POSSIBLE RUBBING AND ABRADEING OF THE INNER CONTENTS AND THEIR BASIC PACKAGE MATERIALS.  THIS SHIPMENT IS BEING HELD UNDER LOCK AND KEY AT ABX AIR, INC. PENDING FAA INVESTIGATION. SEE ATTACHED FOR LIST OF PRODUCTS CONTAINED IN THE BOXES. WE WERE CLEAR OF SCENE AT 12:25. SAME AS REMARKS FOR 95081013A

column168: ON 07/25/95 AT APPROXIMATELY 0242 HOURS, JEFF MCLAUGHLIN/HAZMAT TECHNICIAN, ABX AIR, INC 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGONT OH INVESTIGATED A LEAKING SHIPMENT IN THE UNLOAD OF A OUR SORT FACILITY AT THE SAME ADDRESS. THERE WERE NO HAZARD MARKINGS OR LABELS ON THE OUTSIDE OF THE FIBERBOARD BOX.  THERE WAS NO SHIPPERS CERTIFICAITON ACCOMPANYING THE SHIPMENT. INSIDE THE FIBREBOARD BOX THERE WERE 6 CONTAINERS CONTAINING 6 DIFFERENT PRODUCTS.

WHEN ROAD DRIVER, BALFOUR, ARRIVED BR TERMINAL ON SAT 7/15 SHORTLY AFTER 11AM, HE NOTICED SOMETHING LEAKING OUT THE BACK OF HIS TRAILER & ADVISED THE DISPATCHER. WHEN THE TRAILER DOOR WAS OPENED, EVERYONE WAS TAKEN ABACK BY THE SEVERITY OF THE FUMES AND THE TRAILER WAS PUT OUT INTO THE YARD TO AIR OUT RATHER THAN UP TO THE DOCK. WHEN THE TRAILER WAS PUT INTO THE DOCK ON MONDAY, TWO FO OUR DOCKMEN WORKED THE HALF-LOADED TRAILER DOWN TO FIND THE DRUM, WHICH WAS APPROXIMATELY 1/4 OF THE WAY UP INTO THE NOSE OF THE LEFTHAND SIDE. THERE WAS A SPEAR MARK APPROXIMATELY 2 1/2 TO 3 INCHES LONG ABOUT 3-4" FROM BOTTOM OF THE DRUM. THE ENTIRE TRAILER FLOOR WAS COVERED WITH THIS RESIN AND TO DATE THE DRUM HAS ONLY ABOUT 2 OR 3 GALLONS LEFT IN IT. AS OF TODAY'S DATE THE TRAILER IS BACK OUT IN OUR YARD AIRING OUT SOME MORE. THE RESIN IS NOT YET HARD. THE SHIPPER HAS BEEN ADVISED AND WE ARE AWAITING DISPOSITION ONT HE BALANCE OF THE CONTENTS OF THE DRUM & THE DRUM ITSELF. THE FREIGHT WAS TRANSFERRED AT THE DETROIT TERMINAL WHERE INCIDENT HAD TO HAVE OCCURRED.

THE TEAM OPENED THE PACKAGE IN QUESTION AND FOUND SEVEN INNER RECEPTACLES, SOME GLASS, AND SOME PLASTIC OF VARIOUS TYPES OF CHEMICALS AND A BAG "PILLOW TYPE" DIMS OF THE BAG ARE APPROX 12" X 8" AND IT IS NOT KNOWN IF THIS BAG CONTAINS A CHEMICAL OR IS AN ABSORBENT PILLOW. THE CERT TEAM CONFIRMED THAT ONE OR MORE OF THE INNER RECEPTACLES HAD LEAKED, BUT DUE TO TIME CONSTRAINTS WAS UNABLE TO DO A THOROUGH VISUAL INSPECTION. THE CERT TEAM TRIPLE BAGGED THE SHIPMENT IN QUESTION AND RETURNED TO THE HAZ MAT SORT BUIDLING AND PLACED THE SHIPMENT IN AN APPROVED CORROSIVE CABINET UNDER LOCK AND KEY. THE SHIPMENT WAS TURNED OVER TO HAZARDOUS MATERIALS COORDINATOR BEN TAYLOR FOR FURTHER INVESTIGATION. THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELS OR PROPER CERTIFICATION ACCOMPANYING THIS SHIPMENT TO INDICATE THE CONTENTS WERE REGUALTED AS HAZ MAT. SEE REPORT #95090240A SEE REPORT # 95090240A. column168: HAZMAT SPECIAL AGENT SMITH WAS NOTIFIED OF THE ABOVE TRAILER LEAKING A LIQUID FROM THE UNDERSIDE OF THE TRAILER. THE TRAILER WAS PLACARDED CORROSIVE WITH UN1789. INSPECTION REVEALED THAT THERE WAS A INTERSPERSED, MIXED LOAD OF METAL AND PLASTIC DRUMS WITH TWO PIECES OF WOODEN 2X4 FOR BLOCKING AND BRACING. THE LOAD HAD SHIFTED CAUSING THE DOORS TO BULDGE SLIGHTLY AND THE 2X4 BLOCKING TO BECOME LOOSENED. THE NAILS THAT HELD THE 2X4 TO THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER PUNCTURED ONE PLASTIC DRUM BOTH AT THE REAR OF THE TRAILER. SEVEN MORE PLASTIC DRUM WHILE CARGO SHIFTING CAUSED A CRACK TO APPEAR IN A METAL DRUM, BUNGS DISLODGED BY FLEXING PLASTIC DRUMS DUE TO OTHER CARGO DUE TO BEING CRUSHED BY SHIFTING CARGO. THREE PLASTIC DRUMS WERE OVERPACKED AND TWO METAL DRUMS OVERPACKED. NONE OF THE DRUMS METAL OR PLASTIC HAD ANY WARNING LABELS ON THEM. AFTER HOURS SHIPPER CONTACT WAS MADE IMPOSSIBLE BECAUSE THE SHIPPER OR CONSIGNEE NEITHER ONE IS LISTED WITH CHEMTREC ALTHOUGH THE CHEMTREC NUMBER WAS LISTED AS THE EMERGENCY CONTACT NUMBER. WHEN BUSINESS HOUR CONTACT WAS MADE WITH THE THIRD PARTY BROKER, HERM DYCK OF EASYWAY FREIGHT, 1586 LIVE OAK DRIVE, MISSISSAUGA, ONT, CANADA HE REFUSED TO ALLOW DIRECT CONTACT OR SUPPLY INFORMATION FOR DIRECT CONTACT WITH THE PRODUCT MAKER. THERE ARE NO WARING LABLES ON ANY OF THE DRUMS ARE AS FOLLOWS; IAMSA CATALIZADOR/ENCAPSULANTE. SEE REPORT 95090754A

column168: AN UNLOADER (JOE CHELLAND) FOUND THE PACKAGE.  HE DIDN'T TOUCH IT BUT LEFT THE AREA AND NOTIFIED A SUPERVISOR. column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails); Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: DEAN C. COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED BY DENNY YARD, OPERATIONS MANAGER, ITS, UNION PACIFIC INTERMODAL FACILITY, LOS ANGELES, CALIFORNIA, THAT A CONTAINER WAS NOTED LEAKING AN UNKNOWN SUBSTANCE FROM THE REAR DOORS OF THE CONTAINER AS IT WAS BEING GROUNDED FROM THE RAIL CAR.  AS THE CONTAINER WAS PLACARDED FLAMMABLE, IT WAS MOVED TO TRAILER STORAGE LOT #16 AND ISOLATED PENDING INSPECTION. MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE INTERMODAL FACILITY AND FOUND A DARK LIQUID SEEPING FROM THE REAR DOORS.  SEAL S719355 WAS REMOVED AND THE RIGHT DOOR OPENED TO INSPECT THE LADING.  EXTREMELY STRONG XYLENE VAPORS WERE NOT AT THE DOORWAY.  THE LADING STARTED APPROXIMATELY EIGHT FEET INTO THE CONTAINER AND WAS MIXED CARTONS OF FREIGHT ON PALLETS, FLOOR LOADED, SIDE BY SIDE, WITH THE ONLY ATTEMPT AT BLOCKING AND BRACING BEING A SINGLE 2 X 4 SET INTO THE CONTAINER WALL CORRUGATIONS, RUNNING FROM SIDE TO SIDE. DUE TO THE HIGH FLAMMABLE VAPOR CONCENTRATIONS FROM THE PRODUCT, THE CONTAINER WAS VENTILATED PRIOR TO ENTRY.  CONTACT WAS MADE WITH MR. STEVE TAUB, GENERAL MANAGER, CONTERM, COMPTON, WHICH WAS THE DESTINATION OF THE CONTENTS, WHO PROVIDED A CONTACT WITH THE SHIPPER, CONTERM, BAYONNE, NEW JERSEY. CONTACTED MR. ALLEN MATULA, OPERATIONS MANAGER, FOR CONTERM, WHO STATED THE PRODUCT WAS ACTUALLY LOADED BY A CONTRACT WAREHOUSE LOCATED IN AVENEL, NEW JERSEY.  ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE WITH MR. MATULA TO CONTACT ENVIRONMENTAL TRANSLOADING SERVICES TO EFFECT A TRANSLOAD OF THE LADING. ONCE THE TRANSFER CONTRACT WAS IN PLACE, THE RAILROAD PROVIDED A FORTY FOOT HIGHWAY TRAILER, REAZ240605, FOR THE TRANSFER OPERATION, WHICH STARTED ON TUESDAY AUGUST 1, 1995.  BY ALLOWING THE CONTAINER TO VENTILATE THROUGH OUT THE PREVIOUS NIGHT, THE VAPOR CONCENTRATIONS WERE BELOW ONE PERCENT OF THE LEL, HOWEVER, CONTINUOUS VENTILATION WAS MAINTAINED THROUGH OUT THE TRANSFER OPERATION.  UPON REMOVING THE FIRST PALLET OF FREIGHT FROM THE LEFT SIDE OF THE CONTAINER, LOCATED ONE 55 GALLON DRUM ON A PALET DIRECTLY BEHIND IT.  UPON REMOVAL OF THIS DRUM, THERE WAS LIQUID NOTED DRIPPING FROM THE PALLET.  THE STRETCH WRAP WAS REMOVED AND THE DRUM LIFTED FROM THE PALLET, WHERE A LEAK WAS OBSERVED FROM THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM.  CLOSER INSPECTION DEVELOPED THERE WERE TWO VERY SMALL (APPROXIMATELY 1/32 OF AN INCH) PIN HOLES IN THE CENTER OF THE BOTTOM PORTION THE DRUM.  NORMAL PUNCTURES WOULD HAVE SOME INDENTATION, HOWEVER THERE WAS NO EVIDENCE OF THE METAL BEING INFORMED.  THE AREA AROUND THE TWO HOLES WAS PERFECTLY FLAT, AND SHOWED NO SIGNS OF INTERNAL CORROSION. THERE WAS NO PROTRUSIONS LOCATED ON THE PALLET FROM WHICH THE DRUM WAS SITTING, AND IT IS NOT KNOWN HOW THE DRUM BECAME PUNCTURED.  THE DRUM WAS PLACED INTO AN OVERPACK THE DRUM BECAME PUNCTURED.  THE DRUM WAS PLACED INTO AN OVERPACK TO SECURE THE REMAINING PRODUCT.  THE REMAINING DRUMS WERE REMOVED FROM THE CONTAINER, INSPECTED, AND FOUND TO BE INTACT.  THE REMAINING DRUMS WERE ALL PLACED FOUR DRUMS TO A PALLET, AND
PACKAGE PICKED UP FROM HUB SECONDARY.  STAINED BOX.  BROUGHT BACK TO DMP CAGE FOR PROCESSING.
